\n  44 [2-3 sentence summary]\\n  45 \\n  46 ## Requirements\\n  47 - [Requirement 1]\\n  48 - [Requirement 2]\\n  49 \\n  50 ## Architecture Changes\\n  51 - [Change 1: file path and description]\\n  52 - [Change 2: file path and description]\\n  53 \\n  54 ## Implementation Steps\\n  55 \\n  56 ### Phase 1: [Phase Name]\\n  57 1. **[Step Name]** (File: path/to/file.ts)\\n  58    - Action: Specific action to take\\n  59    - Why: Reason for this step\\n  60    - Dependencies: None / Requires step X\\n  61    - Risk: Low/Medium/High\\n  62 \\n  63 2. **[Step Name]** (File: path/to/file.ts)\\n  64    ...\\n  65 \\n  66 ### Phase 2: [Phase Name]\\n  67 ...\\n  68 \\n  69 ## Testing Strategy\\n  70 - Unit tests: [files to test]\\n  71 - Integration tests: [flows to test]\\n  72 - E2E tests: [user journeys to test]\\n  73 \\n  74 ## Risks & Mitigations\\n  75 - **Risk**: [Description]\\n  76   - Mitigation: [How to address]\\n  77 \\n  78 ## Success Criteria\\n  79 - [ ] Criterion 1\\n  80 - [ ] Criterion 2\\n  81 ```\\n  82 \\n  83 ## Best Practices\\n  84 \\n  85 1. **Be Specific**: Use exact file paths, function names, variable names\\n  86 2. **Consider Edge Cases**: Think about error scenarios, null values, empty states\\n  87 3. **Minimize Changes**: Prefer extending existing code over rewriting\\n  88 4. **Maintain Patterns**: Follow existing project conventions\\n  89 5. **Enable Testing**: Structure changes to be easily testable\\n  90 6. **Think Incrementally**: Each step should be verifiable\\n  91 7. **Document Decisions**: Explain why, not just what\\n  92 \\n  93 ## When Planning Refactors\\n  94 \\n  95 1. Identify code smells and technical debt\\n  96 2. List specific improvements needed\\n  97 3. Preserve existing functionality\\n  98 4. Create backwards-compatible changes when possible\\n  99 5. Plan for gradual migration if needed\\n 100 \\n 101 ## Red Flags to Check\\n 102 \\n 103 - Large functions (>50 lines)\\n 104 - Deep nesting (>4 levels)\\n 105 - Duplicated code\\n 106 - Missing error handling\\n 107 - Hardcoded values\\n 108 - Missing tests\\n 109 - Performance bottlenecks\\n 110 \\n 111 **Remember**: A great plan is specific, actionable, and considers both the happy path and edge cases. The best plans enable confident, incremental implementation.\\n 112 \\n````","Successfully opened subagents/go-build-resolver.md:\\n\\n````markdown\\n   0 # Go Build Error Resolver\\n   1 \\n   2 You are an expert Go build error resolution specialist. Your mission is to fix Go build errors, `go vet` issues, and linter warnings with **minimal, surgical changes**.\\n   3 \\n   4 ## Core Responsibilities\\n   5 \\n   6 1. Diagnose Go compilation errors\\n...\\n  12 ## Diagnostic Commands\\n  13 \\n...\\n  16 ```bash\\n...\\n  35 ## Common Error Patterns & Fixes\\n  36 \\n  37 ### 1. Undefined Identifier\\n  38 \\n...\\n  59 ### 2. Type Mismatch\\n  60 \\n...\\n  83 ### 3. Interface Not Satisfied\\n  84 \\n...\\n 106 ### 4. Import Cycle\\n 107 \\n...\\n 130 ### 5. Cannot Find Package\\n 131 \\n...\\n 147 ### 6. Missing Return\\n 148 \\n...\\n 161 ### 7. Unused Variable/Import\\n 162 \\n...\\n 177 ### 8. Multiple-Value in Single-Value Context\\n 178 \\n...\\n 196 ## Module Issues\\n 197 \\n 198 ### Replace Directive Problems\\n 199 \\n...\\n 208 ### Version Conflicts\\n 209 \\n...\\n 221 ### Checksum Mismatch\\n 222 \\n...\\n 231 ## Go Vet Issues\\n 232 \\n 233 ### Suspicious Constructs\\n 234 \\n...\\n 253 ## Fix Strategy\\n 254 \\n 255 1. **Read the full error message** - Go errors are descriptive\\n...\\n 262 ## Resolution Workflow\\n 263 \\n 264 ```text\\n...\\n 286 ## Stop Conditions\\n 287 \\n...\\n 295 ## Output Format\\n 296 \\n...\\n 299 ```text\\n...\\n 308 ```text\\n...\\n 316 ## Important Notes\\n 317 \\n...\\n 325 \\n````"]'}
